John Edward: Essential Linguistic Skills for Global Citizens
Private schools in Scotland hold the record for academic excellence and this has continued in 2018 with another series of excellent results in exams, further reinforced by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other fields.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS), are trying to offer the highest level of service to students and their parents.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for further education at the highest levels, for their chosen career and their country as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a customized educational curriculum, we are proving how the branch of modern languages continues to be a widespread and popular choice across schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, "If you speak to someone in a language they understand, your words go to their ears.
If you speak to him in your own language, your words go to the heart.”
These words are a powerful reminder that we can't rely only on English when we want to build relationships with people from foreign countries.
From the results of this year's recent tests, we can see that languages are leading the list of results, with the highest level of passing grades among private schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who have studied foreign languages have received the maximum grade A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students had received the maximum grade A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French and 63 percent of those who studied French.
This shows that private schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as one of the vital skills that will undoubtedly be needed for children and young people in the future.
Currently, the branch of foreign languages is considered as important as the branches of STEM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of private schools and beyond.
A 2014 study by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills found that among the main difficulties faced by employers in filling out vacancies, 17 percent of them were related to the lack of language skills.
As a result, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary for the preparation of young people for their future careers.
With the addition of workplaces that have the condition of mastering foreign languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have real advantages in the future, as the owner of such a long-term ability.
The ability to communicate directly with foreign people will automatically position a multilingual person over the competitors.
According to a YouGov poll, which included more than 4,000 adults from the UK in 2013, 75 percent of them were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to develop a conversation, and French was the only foreign language to speak 2 languages.
That's why investing in language learning is important for today's children.
The mastering of many languages, especially the mastering of the languages of developing countries, will give children a better chance of employment.
Within Scotland, each school will be different in terms of the languages that are taught in them.
Some schools will focus on more classic modern languages, while others will offer languages that are considered to be most important for the UK in the 2020 outlook, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a range of languages you can choose from in private schools, with educational staff composed of field specialists.
Scottish private schools are committed to providing a school environment that will prepare children and "arm them" with the skills they need to get out of it, regardless of the future.
At this time it cannot be denied that in a global business environment, languages continue to have a vital importance for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should really be regarded as “the ability of international communication.”
Private schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to the young people of Scotland.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Private Schools.
