Harvard students get lessons on how to get enough rest.
A new course at Harvard University this year has included all students to sleep more, in an effort to combat the growing culture of ‘masks’ of study through the use of caffeine from these ‘sleepers.’
An academic noted that university students number one in the world, often don't know when it comes to the most basic things about how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham's and Women's Hospital, prepared the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start this course after giving a report on the impact that sleep deprivation has on learning.
"At the end of it, a girl approached me and said, 'Why is this thing being told to me now, in my last year?'
She said no one had spoken to her before about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, included in the program for the first time this year, explains to students the necessary elements of how the habits of a good sleep help academic and athletic performance, as well as how it improves their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general director of medical services at the university, said the university decided to introduce this course after finding that students were seriously deprived of sleep during the week.
The course that lasts one hour involves a number of interoperability tasks.
On one side is a view of a convection room, where students click on the coffee cupboards, curtains, athletes and books in order to explain to them the effects of caffeine and lighting and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, as well as the importance of showering on the bedtime routine.
In another part, participants are explained how sleep deprivation over a long period of time increases the risk of heart attack, ischemia, depression, and cancer.
A map of the camp, with an interactive icon, further encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that the behavior of the students will not change immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know - as you have the right to know, the health impact when you choose to smoke," added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride in spending ‘one night’ sleep continues to exist, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students meant that deprivation of sleep was an ever-increasing problem.
Ensuring that you’ve taken enough sleep, of a good quality, should be the students’ ‘secret weapon’ to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said – even to avoid weight gain, because deprivation from sleep leads the brain to a starvation mode, making them feel hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies physical and chemical biology, helped Professor Czeisler prepare the course after attending one of his teaching hours last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and had inspired him to return to a course for the whole camp.
He hopes that the next step, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining competing institutions.
Prof. Czeisler recommended that students should set an hour of nap time that when they should go to bed, and also that when they should wake up, and be aware of the damaging effects of ‘blue light’ coming out of the electronic screens and LED lighting, which can trigger the knee-jerk problem.
