Almanac: The inventor of the Geiger scale
And now a page from our almanac of "Sunday Morning: September 30, 1882, As Today 136 years ago and IN VAZHDIM... the day when the next physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the production of what is known as the Geiger scale.
A major pillar of science since then, the Geiger scale has become a major pillar of popular culture as well, as in the 1950 film Coronado Cities, with a cast of seemingly unprofessional scientists such as Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger measurement used to track radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
"When you put these boxes in, you can really hear the effects of atoms released from radioactivity into minerals."
Evans: "Don't tell me, I'm really listening right now!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name continues to live.
